<HEAD>Inmates Seize Guatemalan Prison Farm, Hold Hostages; Deaths Reported</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout, UPDATING with additional reports of dead and
wounded, eyewitness account. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Inmates took over a prison farm Sunday and seized guards and visitors as hostages, news broadcasts said, with as many as five people killed and up to 20 injured. Television station <PERSON> Notisiete </PERSON> said Easter was a visiting day and about 250 prisoners were holding an estimated 400 people hostage, including guards, other inmates and visiting families with children. Notisiete broadcast reports, which were not confirmed by officials, said three guards and two inmates were killed. A private radio station, <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasters </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Patrol </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, reported that at least two guards and two inmates were killed and 20 people were injured. Neither report gave any indication of the cause of the uprising at the <LOCATION> Pavon </LOCATION> prison farm 12 miles east of <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. The takeover began early Sunday afternoon and continued into the night, local television and radio stations reported. Witnesses said firefighters and <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> workers were seen entering the prison with five stretchers. Prison officials and the national police refused to comment on the situation. Television newscasts showed the prison farm surrounded by police and soldiers sent from the capital. An air force helicopter hovered overhead. <PERSON> Notisiete </PERSON> said additional army units were on standby. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasters </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Patrol </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> broadcast an interview with a man identified as <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Morales </PERSON> who said he and his wife <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> were waiting outside to visit a family member when the revolt began. <PERSON> Morales </PERSON> told the radio station his wife was among about 20 people who were wounded in a gunfight between inmates and guards. He said his wife was taken to a police hospital and he did not know the extent of her injuries. He said he took his wounded wife into a nearby prison chapel where many other visitors sought refuge and where other injured were being cared for. Reports said officials tried to bargain with prisoners to get them to surrender rifles they grabbed from prison guards, and then most of the weapons were recovered after a gun battle. The reports said negotiations were continuing. Notisiete quoted Fire Department Cmdr. <PERSON> Alejandro </PERSON> <PERSON> Giammattei </PERSON> <PERSON> Falla </PERSON> as saying the inmates demanded to talk with federal human rights director <PERSON> Gonzalo </PERSON> <PERSON> Mendez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> la </PERSON> <PERSON> Riva </PERSON> and that journalists and medical workers be allowed to enter the prison.
