<HEAD>Laos Holds First Elections for Ruling Council</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOLLY YONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENTIANE, Laos (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Laotians voted to elect their ruling national council for the first time Sunday in polling that some foreign analysts described as a public relations exercise by Communist leaders. A senior <LOCATION> Laotian </LOCATION> official said no major changes will be made in the Communist autocracy that has governed the country for 13 years. Hundreds were already lined up at polling places at schools, <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> temples and government offices in this capital city when the polls opened in the morning. The 1.8 million eligible voters of this impoverished Southeast Asian nation of 3.8 million people were electing the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, the highest state body. Officials said 121 candidates, mostly <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> members, are running for 79 seats on the body. The council was established when the Communists seized power in December 1975. Some foreign analysts said the election is intended to convince the world <LOCATION> Laos </LOCATION> was stable and an attractive country for foreign investment, trade and foreign aid. In an interview last week, <LOCATION> Thai </LOCATION> political scientist <PERSON> Sirichai </PERSON> <PERSON> Sirikai </PERSON> said the election is designed only to consolidate the power of the Communist hierarchy and convince the world of <LOCATION> Laos </LOCATION>' political stability As he arrived at a temple to cast his ballot, <PERSON> Sisomphon </PERSON> <PERSON> Lavansay </PERSON>, the chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, was asked by journalists about reports of major government changes following the election. `` There will be no changes,'' he replied, adding that the council will not select a new premier. <PERSON> Sisomphon </PERSON> refused to reply when asked if he would be retiring. <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>'s ambassador to <LOCATION> Laos </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Thai </LOCATION> media had quoted reports that some elderly officials may retire after the election, including Prime Minister <PERSON> Kaysone </PERSON> <PERSON> Phomvihane </PERSON>, 68; acting President <PERSON> Phoumi </PERSON> <PERSON> Vongvichit </PERSON>, 80; and <PERSON> Sisomphon </PERSON>, 72. However, <PERSON> Somsavath </PERSON> <PERSON> Lengsavad </PERSON>, permanent secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, had called the election `` another step toward socialist democracy.'' He said results from the country's 4,153 polling stations would be counted by hand, and the final tally would not be known for a week to 10 days. The first nationwide district and provincial elections were held last year.
