<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Millions of Soviets filled out ballots providing a choice of candidates for the first time Sunday in parliamentary elections that President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> called a triumph for his vision of democracy. However, maverick candidate <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON>, running to represent <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> in the new <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deputies </ORGANIZATION>, claimed many people are worried about the possibility of vote fraud and ballot-box stuffing. He complained that the elections were n't completely democratic <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> polling stations, brightly lit and festooned with red banners and Soviet flags, opened at 7 a.m. Observers reported light voter turnout in the morning, but the official <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency said more people were heading for the polls later in the morning. Voters will elect 1,500 deputies of the new 2,250-member congress, which later will choose the country's president and elect from its own ranks delegates to a new full-time Supreme Soviet legislature. The congress itself will meet once a year. Official public organizations, ranging from the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> to a national association for book lovers, are directly electing 750 delegates to the new assembly. In Sunday's voting, hundreds of races were being contested for the first time in 70 years, a major change in Soviet politics. In the past, the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> has allowed only one approved candidate to run for each seat. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, who voted with his wife <PERSON> Raisa </PERSON> at a polling station at <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Institute <