<HEAD>Pope Says Easter Gives Strength to Often Oppressed World</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANCES D'EMILIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> proclaimed an Easter Sunday message of hope tinged with sadness, recalling those persecuted for their faith, the breakup of families, and sectarian strife. About 100,000 pilgrims, tourists and Romans jammed into Saint <PERSON> Peter </PERSON>'s square to hear the pope say mid-morning Easter Mass on the steps of Christianity's largest basilica. He later moved to the balcony to deliver his speech and Easter greetings in 55 languages. By then, the crowd had nearly doubled, spilling over into narrow and cobblestone streets surrounding <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. Keeping with Easter tradition, the <PERSON> pope </PERSON>, who is head of the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> and titular bishop of <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>, delivered his Easter message `` Urbi et Orbi,'' Latin meaning `` to the city and the world.'' On Easter, Christians celebrate their belief in the resurrection of Christ from his tomb following his death on the cross on Good Friday. Calling Easter `` the new Passover,'' in reference to the night the Jews were miraculously saved in <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> said: `` God continues to pass -LRB- through the world -RRB- through the resurrection of his son, the son of man ...'' `` God passes and frees from the fear that oppresses so many of our brothers and sisters,'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> said. `` He passes where there do not exist conditions worthy of a truly human life,'' the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> added. He cited poor housing, broken marriages, prostitution, and countries where people can not freely worship. He did not name any country. `` God passes where ... the longed-for peace is not yet to be seen,'' the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> said, singling out sectarian strife in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. `` God still passes and sets free the whole of creation ... In his blood all is reconciled: man with God, with himself, with nature,'' the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> said. `` At this point, the responsibility of man gains new strength and awareness ... `` This is the truth which Easter proclaims to today's world, which is so many ways seems to be rushing headlong towards self-destruction and death,'' the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> said.
