<HEAD>Rejection Of Begin Play Highlights Ambivalence Toward Leader</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Peace-Anniversary, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In a new play about <PERSON> Menachem </PERSON> <PERSON> Begin </PERSON>, the enigmatic former <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> leader fantasizes about bombing <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> to retaliate for the Holocaust and imagines being mobbed by admirers after ending his self-imposed seclusion. The one-man play was written for the <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> Festival in May but was rejected by festival officials who feared such free-wheeling treatment of the 75-year-old Begin was too controversial. The rejection highlights the ambivalence and strong emotions Begin still generates among Israelis nearly six years after he unexpectedly resigned as prime minister and shut himself in his two-story apartment at the edge of the <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> pine forest. `` To the nationalists, Begin is a sacred man, a symbol of everything that is pure and good. To those on the left, he stands for everything they despise,'' said <PERSON> Ehud </PERSON> <PERSON> Sprinzak </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Hebrew </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> professor and expert on right-wing Israeli politics. Begin became prime minister in 1977, the first from the right-wing <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> bloc to hold the post. Two years later, he signed the historic peace treaty with <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, sharing the Nobel Peace Prize with President <PERSON> Anwar </PERSON> <PERSON> Sadat </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>. He resigned in 1983 at the height of the war in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. Today, Begin's life is shrouded in mystery, frustrating biographers and heightening curiosity among Israelis. He ventures outside his apartment for a public appearance only once a year to attend a memorial service for his wife, <PERSON> Aliza </PERSON>, who died in 1982. Begin breaks his silence rarely, usually to comment briefly on the radio about history. He refuses to discuss his resignation, commonly attributed to depression over the death of his wife and the <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> war, in which more than 600 Israelis died. On Sunday, Begin commented on the 10th anniversary of the Israel-Egypt peace accord, taking the unusual step of speaking about current politics and criticizing the new American dialogue with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> as `` a negative, harmful phenomenon.'' He spends his days reading books, mostly biographies and history, said longtime Begin aide <PERSON> Yehiel </PERSON> <PERSON> Kadishai </PERSON>. He said Begin keeps up with news programs, reads <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> and foreign newspapers, and answers several dozen letters a week. Once an avid movie-goer, he now watches videos in the evenings. `` He likes Westerns,'' said <PERSON> Kadishai </PERSON>, adding that the former prime minister also used to watch the American soap opera `` <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>.'' American oil magnate <PERSON> Armand </PERSON> <PERSON> Hammer </PERSON> offered to donate $ 750,000 to Begin's favorite charity if the former prime minister wrote his autobiography, but <PERSON> Begin </PERSON> has declined, <PERSON> Kadishai </PERSON> said. His family, aides and friends refuse to talk about Begin in what <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> journalists have described as a wall of silence. Justice Minister <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Meridor </PERSON>, a longtime friend, visits Begin every Friday to talk politics. When asked for details about the talks, <PERSON> Meridor </PERSON> balked. `` I've never spoken about my conversations with Begin.'' <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> journalist <PERSON> Amnon </PERSON> <PERSON> Dankner </PERSON> tried to skirt these obstacles and probe the former prime minister's psyche in his one-man play, titled simply `` Begin.'' In one scene, <PERSON> Begin </PERSON> imagines ending his seclusion. `` People will see me and will be amazed,'' he says, dreaming of a crowd cheering and shouting `` long live Begin.'' But then he stops himself and asks: `` What would be the point of all those years? All the silence, the self-imprisonment?'' In another scene, Begin fantasizes about ordering a strike against <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> in retaliation for the Nazi Holocaust in which 6 million Jews, including Begin's parents and brother, were killed. `` On that day, bodies would pile up at the entrances of towns and squares, like they were piled up at the entrances of the camps,'' says the Begin character. <PERSON> Dankner </PERSON> said he and many other Israelis share these revenge fantasies, adding that Begin's ability to articulate such emotions was at the root of his popularity. `` In every Israeli, there is a little Begin,'' he said. `` He expressed our fears, our nightmares, our delusions of grandeur.'' Even today, the mention of Begin sparks strong reactions. During an election rally last fall, <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> followers listened politely to speeches by party leaders, but at the mention of Begin's name worked themselves into a frenzy, clapping and shouting the name of the former leader for several minutes. But anger toward Begin has remained just as strong. While Begin celebrated his birthday last summer, a crowd gathered outside his apartment, including a <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> woman whose son was killed in the June 1982 <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> invasion. `` This man caused dozens of young men not to reach even their 20th birthdays,'' said the woman, <PERSON> Raya </PERSON> <PERSON> Harnik </PERSON>. `` In the middle of the war he just said he could n't go on any longer. The bereaved parents never had such a privilege.''
