<SECOND>AM-Fat Fight, Bjt,760</SECOND>
<HEAD>Where There's Smoke There's Hot Grease</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY MASSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A dispute over cooking oils is heating up as farm state lawmakers and consumer groups join ranks on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> in what they say is literally a fight for the hearts of Americans. But underlying it all is a battle that has gone on for months between agricultural producers. The fight matches <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> soybean farmers against foreign palm and coconut growers. `` It's a symptom of increased international competition that we have today for all products,'' says <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Reuwee </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Soybean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. So far, the dispute has produced legislation as well as a war of words in advertisements by both sides. At issue in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is a proposal by Rep. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Glickman </PERSON>, D-Kan., and Sen. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Harkin </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Iowa </LOCATION>, to require more nutritional information on food packages to help consumers know what vegetable oils are used in products and how much cholesterol-raising saturated fats they contain At issue for producers is their share of the multi-billion-dollar <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and international markets for edible oils, which covers everything from salad dressings, cooking oils to margarine. According to the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, soybean oil accounts for more 70 percent of the edible oils used in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> while the so-called tropical oils _ palm, <LOCATION> palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> kernel </LOCATION> and coconut oils _ represent 4 percent. But internationally, tropical oils dominate and the industry worries that worldwide sales could suffer if the current health scare moves overseas from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> farm group, by its own admission, helped start the fight by persuading lawmakers to introduce legislation in 1987 targeting tropical oils as sources of cholesterol-raising saturated fats. `` We'd be lying if we said we have n't taken advantage of the health issue here to market our crop,'' says <PERSON> Reuwee </PERSON>. `` But it's what any good marketing organization does. Palm growers from <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>, the leading producer of the oil, are striking back with a campaign to promote their product. `` We think we're getting a pretty bum rap from statements that palm oil raises cholesterol when there is n't any evidence whatsoever that this is true,'' says <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Phipps </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Malaysian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Palm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Growers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. The latest development came this month when <PERSON> Glickman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Harkin </PERSON> introduced a new version of the legislation. The lawmakers complained that some products claim to have `` no cholesterol'' or are made with `` 100 percent vegetable shortening'' although they contain cooking oils with high levels of saturated fats. The American <ORGANIZATION> Heart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which supports the legislation, says consumers can reduce the risk of heart disease by lowering the amount of saturated fat in their diet. Lard is 41 percent saturated fat by weight. Palm oil contains 51 percent saturated fat; coconut oil, 92 percent; sunflower oil, 11 percent; corn oil, 13 percent; olive oil, 14 percent; and soybean oil, 15 percent. In general, the legislation would require food labels to clearly list all cooking oils contained in the product or disclose detailed nutrition information, including the amount of total fat, cholesterol and saturated fat. The previous bill would have required labels to identify tropical oils as a `` saturated fat.'' <PERSON> Glickman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Harkin </PERSON> dropped that provision in an effort to avoid continued opposition from tropical oils producers, who blocked the original bill by arguing it represented an international trade barrier. However, <PERSON> Phipps </PERSON> contends the new legislation still will hurt tropical oil producers. `` It is safe to say that it does not really help their predicament. Forcing a food company to put palm oil, coconut or palm kernel oil down as a sole source oil probably would be somewhat of a deterrent for food companies,'' says <PERSON> Phipps </PERSON>. He contends that negative publicity already has hurt the industry. In fact, a group called the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Heart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, led by a millionaire from <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Neb. </LOCATION>, is conducting a national advertising campaign against tropical oils using banner headlines of `` The Poisoning of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' Already nearly a dozen large food companies such as General <PERSON> Mills </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> have announced they have stopped or are phasing out the use of tropical oils from their products. Some products now carry labels that say they contain no palm or coconut oils. Palm growers have countered with full-page ads of their own in some of the nation's largest newspapers, decrying the `` smear campaign'' against tropical oils. The industry also has commissioned 30 scientific studies, including several at <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> universities, on the health effects of palm oil. Last year, the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZ