<HEAD>Dentists Get Bite Put On Them By Superfund</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Disposal of the kind of old dental fillings taken from millions of mouths has <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ott </PERSON>'s family-owned dental supply company battling the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. At the heart of the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s partially-settled dispute with <PERSON> Ott </PERSON>'s company, 58 dentists, three other dental supply concerns and three individuals is how far the government can reach to hold parties accountable for toxic waste contamination <PERSON> Ott </PERSON>'s case has aroused attention on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> because some lawmakers believe the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> has overstepped its bounds in the name of pollution prevention and accountability. The case hinges on amalgam _ the stuff that fillings are made of _ and whether it can be considered a `` hazardous substance'' after it has been removed from peoples' teeth. <PERSON> Ott </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> company, which sells drill bits and other dental equipment, says it bought amalgam from its dentist customers and sold it to a <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> metal reclamation business. Amalgam is a hard, durable alloy of mercury and silver. Dentists often save old fillings or leftover amalgam and sell it to processors, who break it down into mercury or silver. In <PERSON> Ott </PERSON>'s case, the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> alleged that he and others sold amalgam to metal processor <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Bourdeaudhui </PERSON> between 1969 and 1984. As a result of <PERSON> Bourdeaudhui </PERSON>'s efforts to break the amalgam down, the agency said soil in <LOCATION> Willington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, became so polluted with toxic mercury that it required a $ 710,000 cleanup in 1985. In seeking out responsible parties to pay for the cleanup, the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> stunned the nationwide dental community by going after not only <PERSON> Bourdeaudhui </PERSON> but also 58 dentists and several dental suppliers who did business with him. The dentists settled last June with the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>, which then sued the <ORGANIZATION> Ott </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supply </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Benco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supply </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Wilkes-Barre </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>; <ORGANIZATION> A. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Leventhal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sons </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Scranton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>; and <ORGANIZATION> Smith-Holden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Providence </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> R.I. </LOCATION> Also sued were <PERSON> Bourdeaudhui </PERSON>; his former wife, <PERSON> Elsie </PERSON>; and <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Battle </PERSON>, an amalgam broker in <LOCATION> Whitehall </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, who also did business with <PERSON> Bourdeaudhui </PERSON>. On Feb. 16, the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> announced that <ORGANIZATION> Benco </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Leventhal </PERSON> and Mrs. <PERSON> Bourdeaudhui </PERSON> settled for amounts ranging from $ 40,000 to $ 60,000. The other four parties are still battling the suit. <PERSON> Ott </PERSON>'s son, <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON>, 36, said it is difficult for him to grasp that his family's firm, which has six full-time employees, has ended up in a federal court case about dental fillings. `` It's a question of liability and how far it can go,'' the younger <PERSON> Ott </PERSON> said. `` You can break water down into hydrogen and oxygen. The hydrogen could explode and the oxygen could feed the fire.'' <PERSON> Ott </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> suit, which is being heard in a federal court in <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, could wipe out the business that he had hoped to take over from his father. `` The fact that dental amalgam is considered a hazardous waste under Superfund comes as a surprise to many,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Walgren </PERSON>, D-Pa., in a recent letter to <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> `` A substance which is in my mouth _ and the mouths of millions of Americans _ and is deemed ` safe' by dentists and the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> hardly seems a candidate for Superfund coverage.'' Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON>, R-Pa., also wrote the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> last month saying he feared the case could discourage recycling by dentists `` The precedent of making recyclers of products liable for the hazardous byproducts of a recycling process that is not directly in their control creates a major disincentive for recycling,'' <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON> said. But the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> said the case should make dentists and dental suppliers more responsible. In announcing the settlements last month, <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> Regional Administrator <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Deland </PERSON> said the agreements `` demonstrate that members of the dental community understand that they have a responsibility to make themselves aware of dental amalgam's ultimate disposal method and that the dental community _ which controls the disposition of waste amalgam _ rather than taxpayers, should bear the cost of cleanup.
