<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration is reviewing the need for tougher <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> curbs as well as expanded international cooperation to help block the export to Third World countries of chemicals and equipment for making poison gas weapons, a <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official said Sunday. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Freedenberg </PERSON>, undersecretary of commerce for export administration, said the steps could include new legislation or at least bolstered regulations for enforcing current export control statutes. `` We're reviewing the strengthening of controls,'' he said, noting that the policy review was being handled primarily by the State and <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> departments, with some input from the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Freedenberg </PERSON> said he expects the review will be completed in the next few months. `` Most likely we wo n't need legislation, we just need further regulation,'' he said. `` And more importantly, I think it's likely that we'll be looking for international cooperation.'' <PERSON> Freedenberg </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and 16 other industrialized nations have pledged to prevent the export of critical poison-gas chemicals and manufacturing equipment to four `` problem countries'' _ <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>. But there are other mainly Third World countries, he said, which are believed to be interested in developing a chemical-weapons capability. `` You have a country such as <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> _ which is right next door to <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> and obviously has a concern about Libyan capacity to make chemical weapons _ where there are no controls whatsoever on that type of equipment or those chemicals,'' <PERSON> Freedenberg </PERSON> said. Other countries which either have poison gas or are developing the capability of making it include <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>. `` If you want to have a comprehensive, worldwide regime, you have to have a regime that controls both the precursor chemicals and the equipment to make chemical warfare agents to all the world outside of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the other 16 members of the <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> group,'' <PERSON> Freedenberg </PERSON> said. The group of industrialized nations is so called because it was formed at a meeting held at the Australian embassy in <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION> in 1985.
