<HEAD>GOP Spending Doubled Democrats' in 1987-88 Elections</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 During the 1987-88 election cycle the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> raised and spent more than double the amount of money taken in and spent by the Democrats, but the gap between the two parties' financial strength was less than in 1983-84, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> said Sunday. A report issued by the commission said the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> raised $ 263.3 million and spent $ 257 million in 1987-88, compared to $ 127.9 million raised and $ 121.9 million spent by the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. By contrast, when President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> ran for re-election in 1983-84, the Republicans raised a record $ 297.9 million and spent $ 300.8 million, while the Democrats raised $ 98.5 million and spent $ 97.4 million. In 1987-88 the two parties were more closely matched in terms of so-called coordinated expenditures _ monies spent on behalf of federal candidates in the general election but not directly contributed to their campaign coffers. Coordinated expenditures by the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> totalled $ 22.7 million, 27 percent more than the Democrats' $ 17.9 million The <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> figure was nearly double the $ 9 million spent in coordination with general election campaigns in 1983-84, while coordinated expenditures by the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> rose only 13 percent from the $ 20.1 million reported in the earlier two-year period. During the most recent election cycle, direct contributions to candidates totalled $ 3.4 million for the Republicans and $ 1.7 million for the Democrats, the <ORGANIZATION> FEC </ORGANIZATION> said. It reported that of the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION>'s total 1987-88 receipts, 87 percent came from individuals, 3 percent from state and local party organizations, 1 percent from political action committees, or PACs, and 9 percent from other sources. For the Democrats, the breakdown was 68 percent from individuals, 6 percent from state and local parties, 8 percent from PACs and 17 percent from other sources.
