ally an effective way to reduce risk? `` Yes, it is,'' <PERSON> Young </PERSON> replied. `` In the case of fruit, you should be able to, if it is injected in, see the needle site and see the particular softening at that point. It's also important that in the large fruits, like apples, to look at the stem and blossom areas.'' Young, who also headed <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> during the cyanide poisoning of over-the-counter pain medication in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> several years ago, said there are almost always visible signs of tampering. `` What I was impressed with is, when we looked at all of the tampering that we've gone through, that even with medicines, when capsules were involved, any consumer that had looked at the dosage form would have seen that the capsule was tampered with,'' said <PERSON> Young </PERSON>. He denied any suggestion that his call for increased consumer awareness amounted to the agency shirking responsibility. `` I'd say that we have with the resources at hand moved these to meet a variety of crises and we can do that quite well,'' said <PERSON> Young </PERSON>. `` On the other hand, we can not do 100 percent safety. In the case of this inspection, we had to do a random sampling that we then, with a probability, a statistical probability, say that we've got the maximum feasible safety that can be done through inspection.
