> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Physics </ORGANIZATION>, told reporters the occasionally boisterous campaign caused by the multicandidate election was just what the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> leadership wanted. `` The electoral law that we passed has justified our hopes,'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said, as Mrs. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, holding a blue umbrella, stood beside him under a light rain. `` It has advanced the political thought and social activity of the people, and this is what we wanted to achieve.'' The 58-year-old <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, already elected to the congress by the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, picked up a paper ballot, walked to a wooden voting booth and closed the curtain. After 25 seconds he emerged and dropped his ballot in a box. He would not disclose for whom he voted. The president said his policies of pressing for more democracy and openness in Soviet society, while not permitting any legal opposition to the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, are `` the key to opening the potential of our socialist society, with the purpose of taking into account the various interests of people and harmonizing them on the basis of consensus or a majority.'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said political pluralism is `` not a panacea for solving problems and expressing a plurality of opinions.'' Despite calls by some protesters for a multiparty system, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said he was confident most Soviets supported his views. <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON>, attempting a political comeback following his November 1987 ouster as <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s party boss, voted at the <ORGANIZATION> Young </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pioneers </ORGANIZATION> palace in the Soviet capital. He said the elections were `` not fully democratic'' but called them `` a big step forward.'' He told reporters Soviets in particular were `` worried about election results, worried that there will be deviation at election stations during the vote counting. Everything is troubling them.'' <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON>, who has become an anti-establishment figure in the city where he once headed the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> machine, has charged the city's party apparatus is out to sabotage his candidacy. The Moscow-based <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, which counts the ballots, said about 190 million of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s 285 million people are eligible to vote. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said the commission began its round-the-clock job of tabulating returns Sunday night, after receiving telegrams containing preliminary results from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Far </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Isaeev </PERSON> told reporters certified returns for <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> would be made public Monday night. The counting of ballots nationwide is expected to take several days. The election commission is required to make full returns public by April 5. All Soviets over 18 years old are permitted to vote unless they have been certified insane. Nearly 180,000 neighborhood polling stations opened their doors to voters Sunday morning and closed at 8 p.m. local time. Elections in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> were until Sunday carefully choreographed rituals in which practically all eligible voters were said to turn out and those running got 99.9 percent of the vote. Some Soviets expressed satisfaction at finally having a choice, but there were also objections. `` I think the quality of our leaders will improve because now we have a real democracy,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Valentina </PERSON> <PERSON> Agababova </PERSON> as she sat on a windowsill at voting precinct No. 5 in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Sverdlovsk </LOCATION> district, crossing out names of candidates she opposed. `` Once upon a time, we'd just take the forms and throw them into the ballot box. Now, for the first time, we're really voting.'' But in southwestern <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Gagarin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> district </LOCATION>, where 12 candidates were running, `` some old people have gotten upset about having so many choices,'' said local elections secretary <PERSON> Natalya </PERSON> <PERSON> Safonkina </PERSON>. Three Soviet cosmonauts aboard the Mir space station _ <PERSON> Sergei </PERSON> <PERSON> Krikalev </PERSON>, <PERSON> Valery </PERSON> <PERSON> Polyakov </PERSON> and <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Volkov </PERSON> _ cast their ballots from orbit, radioing their choices to ground control in a less-than-secret ballot, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said.
