<HEAD>Yeltsin, In Comeback Bid, Expresses Concern About Election Fairness</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with early, unofficial returns.
Pickup 5th graf pvs: `Large pro-Yeltsin...' ^With AM-Soviet-Election, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON>, the fallen protege of President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, led his rival for parliament by a margin of more than 7.5-to-1 in early, unofficial returns in Sunday's voting. Unofficial returns from three districts of the citywide <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> vote had <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> ahead with 4,069 votes to 532 for <PERSON> Yevgeny </PERSON> <PERSON> Brakov </PERSON>, director of the factory that makes ZIL limousines _ one of the flashiest symbols of Soviet privilege, which <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> targeted in his campaign. Certified returns for the voting in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> would be made public Monday night, said <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Isaeev </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> suggested earlier in the day that the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> might cheat him out of his political comeback by rigging the vote count. Of more than 2,000 Soviets interviewed at polling places after voting, 1,734 were for <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> and 162 for <PERSON> Brakov </PERSON>. Others either refused to disclose how they voted or expressed opposition to either candidate. The informal poll, conducted by Western correspondents, was not a scientifically accurate indicator of the outcome. But it supported <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON>'s claim to widespread popular support, which has surfaced increasingly toward the end of the first seriously contested political race in the Soviet capital at least since the days of <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON>. <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON>'s backers predicted he would win the support of 5 million of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s 6.7 million eligible voters. <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> himself predicted victory but declined to specify a margin. Large pro-Yeltsin rallies were held in the capital in the closing days of the campaign for the new 2,250 <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deputies </ORGANIZATION>, the first seriously contested open political race in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> since the days of <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON> `` People are worried about the election results, worried that there will be deviations at election stations during vote counting,'' <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> told reporters after voting Sunday. `` Everything is troubling them.'' `` Democracy depends on the election procedure, which has n't been tested yet,'' he said. <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON>, 58, who headed <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s powerful <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> bureaucracy and held non-voting membership on the ruling Politburo before his ouster, claims the party worked against his campaign. He accused party officials of restricting public access to his campaign speeches and said they tried to damage his election chances by setting up a commission in the final weeks of the campaign to investigate his conduct. <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> has demanded an end to special privileges for party and government officials, such as access to special stores and chauffeured luxury cars. He also has called for more radical economic reforms to fill empty store shelves. <PERSON> Brakov </PERSON>, 51, has said his top priority is to end food shortages by providing more machinery to farmers and improving storage and processing facilities. When <PERSON> Yeltin </PERSON> was asked if he was satisfied with his campaign for <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s at-large seat in the new congress, he said Sunday: `` Not in its entirety. Maybe it's because there are things we're not used to This leap to democracy had some positive and negative processes.'' The election campaign, he said, was `` not fully democratic'' but was a `` big step forward'' from previous balloting in which only one candidate was put forward for each post. But the real test of democracy will be whether the vote count is fair, <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, who brought <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> into the leadership in 1985 and two years later oversaw his ouster on charges of making political mistakes and displaying personal ambition, said criticism of party officials is normal during campaigns and that <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> was not the only one who received it.
