<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Permitting guards to carry loaded weapons on aircraft will not deter terrorists but could endanger the planes and passengers, a trade union representing airline cabin crews said Sunday. The Observer newspaper reported Sunday that police officers escorting top politicians and members of the royal family are being allowed to carry loaded guns onto British aircraft under security regulations revised after the bombing of <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> Flight 103. Security personnel have been permitted to carry only unloaded firearms onto aircraft. `` The problem is that indiscriminate firing of guns, which could always occur, could create as much damage as anything else,'' said <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryde </PERSON>, national secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>'s civil aviation group. The <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Sunday it would not discuss security matters. The <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> declined comment and <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Yard </LOCATION> said it had `` no knowledge'' of the matter. <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION>, which the Observer identified as one of several airlines affected by the new order, also said it could not comment. <PERSON> Ryde </PERSON> said armed guards on aircraft would do little to deter terrorists. `` If the glass or shell of an aircraft is punctured, it could cause decompression with people being sucked out,'' he said. `` What could an armed guard have done to prevent what happened at <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION>?'' he asked. Investigators have said a bomb caused Flight 103 to explode in midair over <L