<HEAD>General Electric Teaches Computer To Keep An Eye On Takeovers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Scisor is cq throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Takeover strategists, take note: Your future competition may have more in common with R2-D2 than with <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boone </PERSON> <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON> and <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> says it has taught a computer to keep track of mergers and acquisitions by reading the Dow Jones news service ticker. The finance-minded software package, called Scisor, was created by the wife-and-husband team of <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rau </PERSON> and <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacobs </PERSON> at <ORGANIZATION> GE </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Schenectady </LOCATION>, N.Y. The prototype software could be adapted to `` almost any area in which human beings under intense deadline pressure have to struggle through smothering amounts of paperwork,'' <ORGANIZATION> GE </ORGANIZATION> said in an announcement for release Monday. Users can ask the computer questions in simple English and get answers back the same way, <ORGANIZATION> GE </ORGANIZATION> said, giving this example: User: Who received an offer from <LOCATION> Bethlehem </LOCATION> Steel? System: <ORGANIZATION> Bethlehem </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> took over <ORGANIZATION> Rail </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mill </ORGANIZATION>. The colorless language and relatively limited vocabulary of the Dow Jones wire made it ideal for experimentation, Ms. <PERSON> Rau </PERSON> said in an interview last week. Scisor did have some trouble at first with `` sweetened'' bids and `` tender'' offers, she said. `` It's not reasoning with the information. It's simply taking the facts in a story and putting them down. It does n't know if something is true or false or reasonable or unreasonable,'' she said. The Dow Jones wire, also called the `` ticker,'' contains boiled-down company announcements, corporate earnings reports, government actions affecting business and other information of interest to the investment community. The wire, a fixture in investment houses, is part of <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co.. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the publisher of the Wall Street Journal <ORGANIZATION> GE </ORGANIZATION>'s own <ORGANIZATION> Kidder </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peabody </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> brokerage unit is interested in <LOCATION> Scisor </LOCATION> and will be given a demonstration in coming weeks. But <ORGANIZATION> GE </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Gwynne </PERSON> said it may be one or two years before any part of GE begins offering a Scisor-based product. The text enters the computer electronically and the user communicates with the machine through a keyboard. It has a vocabulary of about 10,000 words. The system figures out a text by diagramming sentences in the manner of junior high school English classes. It extracts additional sense by using programmed-in expectations _ for example, that the bigger company is usually the acquiring one. Ms. <PERSON> Rau </PERSON> said some financial people who have seen Scisor in action are surprised how well it does. `` In the distant future, we can imagine the computer not as a static repository of information but as a librarian who not only knows where all the information in the library is kept, but also has read and understood everything in the library,'' Ms. <PERSON> Rau </PERSON> said in the written announcement.
