<HEAD>Multibillion-Dollar Transit System Up For Vote In Congested City</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Trolley Comeback, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `Response to ...,' to CORRECT to half-penny sted
penny tax. Also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MEL REISNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Voters in <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> and its suburbs decide Tuesday whether to add a half-penny to their sales tax to finance an $ 8.4 billion highway and transit program, including a controversial 103-mile elevated railway. The metropolitan area of 2 million people is the nation's largest without an integrated freeway system A vast grid of north-south, east-west streets is stamped across the desert, relieved only by two Interstate highways and a piece of state freeway. <LOCATION> Maricopa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> residents are saddled with some of the highest auto-insurance rates in the nation partly because of intersection collisions. `` The population of this valley is going to double in the future, whether we like it or not,'' says <PERSON> Herb </PERSON> <PERSON> Drinkwater </PERSON>, mayor of the wealthy suburb of <LOCATION> Scottsdale </LOCATION>. `` I've been here 43 years, and I do n't always like it, but we have to deal with it, and there's no way that there can be enough roads built to handle the traffic. `` We've got to get out of our cars and get them off the road.'' Response to Proposition 300 and its addition of a half-penny to the 6-cent sales tax is mixed. Neighborhood preservationists and tax-dollar watchers have lined up against it while expansionists in the metropolitan area called the Valley of the Sun back it. The ambitiousness of the ValTrans proposition can be read in its statistics _ expansion of the bus system from 350 vehicles to 1,500, running longer expanded hours; 23 miles of commuter rail; 27 miles of rapid-transit bus routes; and the 103 miles of automated rapid-transit rail lines. Cost estimates range from $ 8.4 billion to $ 10.4 billion by the year 2019, but proponents call it about $ 44 annually for an average household. Moreover, they say, the system will create 7,000 jobs and will help clean the air over the valley. Air travelers approaching the city may be surprised by a brown haze obscuring nearby mountains. The metropolitan area has just gone through a voluntary program to cut down on car use and other pollution causes. A new state law requires that gasoline be blended with oxygen additives, similar to a program in <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>, six months of the year to cut pollution. <PERSON> Drinkwater </PERSON> said the arguments against <ORGANIZATION> ValTrans </ORGANIZATION> were put forth 25 years ago against creation of a freeway system. That successful fight against unified freeway planning led the current chaotic state of driving here, he said. The only operating freeways in the metropolitan area are Interstate 10, which comes in from the west and bends southeastward toward <LOCATION> Tucson </LOCATION>; Interstate 17, which splits off I-10 and heads north to <LOCATION> Flagstaff </LOCATION>; and State Route 360, the Superstition Freeway, which extends eastward from I-10 in <LOCATION> Mesa </LOCATION>. About 100 miles south, I-10 is the only freeway in <LOCATION> Tucson </LOCATION>. But while that <LOCATION> Pima </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> seat has only about one-third as many people as greater <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION>, a coalition recently unveiled plans for a 1 percent sales-tax hike to raise $ 6.8 billion for transportation and other improvements there. The rail system is the sticking point for most ValTrans opponents. `` We agree that there are traffic-congestion problems,'' says <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Chasse </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Voters </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Against </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senseless </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transit </ORGANIZATION>. `` VAST is not against mass transit but against the part of Proposition 300 that includes 103 miles of light rail.'' He and others said they doubt that Arizonans, accustomed to the California-pioneered style of suburban sprawl and freeway driving, would ever take a train to work. However, <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenfield </PERSON>, an insurance agent in <LOCATION> Scottsdale </LOCATION>, said residents might welcome a chance to use alternative transportation. `` As an individual, I think it's a good idea for the greater good of everybody,'' <PERSON> Greenfield </PERSON> said. `` If it eliminates some of the cars and gets some order to this thing, it's a good idea.''
