<HEAD>Dollar Firms Slightly, Stock Prices Edge Down In Early Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar firmed slightly in early trading against the Japanese yen Monday, while stock prices edged down. The dollar opened at 131.68 yen, up 0.41 yen from Friday's close of 131.27 yen. A dealer with the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> said there was some demand for the dollar but otherwise the market was extremely quiet in the wake of a three-day Easter holiday overseas. On the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Average </ORGANIZATION> of 225 selected issues, a 20.14-point loser Friday, shed another 14.97 points, or 0.04 percent, shortly after the market opened to move to 31,553.55. Currency and stock markets in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> will reopen Monday, while both markets in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> will be closed until Tuesday.
